description:
The President of Botswana has, in accordance with regulation 5 (1) and (4) of the Emergency Powers (COVID-19) Regulations, 2020, and on evidence submitted to him by the Director of Health Services that the risks posed by COVID-19 have increased in Botswana and declared that a person shall not travel across a COVID zone without a movement permit, subject to the following –
(a) a person who had travelled across COVID zones with a valid movement permit prior to the publication of this Notice may, where applicable, return before the expiration of the movement permit;
(b) a person with a medical emergency may apply for a movement permit to travel across COVID zones to access health facilities;
(c) a person assisting the person referred to in paragraph (b) may apply for a movement permit to travel across COVID zones to access health facilities;
(d) an essential service provider may apply for a movement permit to travel across COVID zones to provide essential services; and
(e) a person may apply for a movement permit to travel across COVID zones to – (i) attend a funeral of an immediate member of his or her family, and in this subparagraph “immediate member of the family” means a spouse, son, daughter, sibling or parent, or (ii) access a farm, ranch, garden, ploughing field (masimo) or cattle post (moraka)

The President of Botswana declared, in accordance with regulation 5 (4) of the Emergency Powers (COVID-19) Regulations, 2020 that from the 7th of September, 2021 to the 30th of September 2021, all gatherings are suspended, with the exception of the following —
(a) a meeting of Cabinet;
( ) a meeting of the National Assembly;
(c) a meeting of a Council;
(d) a meeting of the National Task Force on COVID-19;
(e) a meeting or workshop with a maximum of 50 persons attending for a maximum of two hours; and
(f) such other gatherings as the Director of Health Services may authorise.

The Botswana government announced that a person in a public place shall maintain a social distance of one to two  metres from another person in a gathering, a place of trade or business, a school;   
an industry or place where goods or services are offered to the public; 
and a public place or any place accessible to the public.
